<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12060l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12060l">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12060l"> 60(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> de meo tergo / degitur corium</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Dans les contes des Bretons armoricains <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> il est souvent fait mention d&apos;une &eacute;trange coutume d&apos;apr&egrave;s laquelle, lorsqu&apos;un engagement lie deux hommes, celui qui manque &agrave; sa parole se laisse tailler une bande de peau depuis le sommet de la t&ecirc;te jusqu&apos;&agrave; la plante des pieds, et n&apos;essaie point de se soustraire &agrave; cette torture. C&apos;est peut-&ecirc;tre au souvenir d&apos;une semblable coutume que se rattachent ces paroles de Plaute, souvent cit&eacute;es: de meo tergo degitur corium (c&apos;est &agrave; mes risques et p&eacute;rils que l&apos;on fait la chose). <br><font color="green">[In the stories of the Armorican Bretons mention is often made of a strange custom. When a man breaks an agreement with another man, he allows him to cut a single strip of skin from the top of his head to the sole of his feet and he does not try to escape from this torture. Maybe it is the memory of a similar custom that inspired Plautus the words that are so often quoted: <i><mark>de meo tergo degitur corium</mark></i> (this is done at my peril)]</font> <small> L-F. Sauv&eacute, <a name="LFSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LFSP"><cite title="source">Proverbes et dictons de la Basse-Bretagne</cite></a> (1878) 93n1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
